\fs36 Notes on the Creation of the TrueType Files
\fs24 \
I reduced the size of the TeXGyreHeros font by 10%, in the following manner.  In FontForge, Edit > Select > Glyphs worth outputting.  Followed by, Element > Transformations > Transform, Select  Scale uniformly 90%, Glyph Origin.  \
\
When I went to save TeXGyreHeros as .ttf files, font forge pointed out that, "The convention is that TrueType fonts should have an Em-size which is a power of 2."  Each of the .otf font files have sizes of 1000. (In FontForge, Element > Font Info > General) Comparing the character sizes in TeXGyreHeros to those in a Helvetica.ttf, I decided to increase the size to 2^11 = 2048, and then save them as .ttf files.  \
\
I expected to use font forge to just combine the TeXGyreHeros fonts with the ntxmia and ntxmi fonts from the newtx package.  Unfortunately, ntxmia and ntxmi are virtual fonts, which combine characters from several fonts to make new virtual fonts.  Tracking everything down would have been a large effort. (see http://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/151872/convert-certain-newtx-fonts-to-truetype-or-opentype) Instead I noted that the primary fonts ntxmia and ntxmi pull from are txmia.pfb and rtxmi.pfb from the old txfonts package.  As far as I can tell, all the characters I care about (the greek letters) are in txmia.pfb and rtxmi.pfb.  Similar to TeXGyreHeros, I had to change the Em-size setting to 2048 when I saved txmia and rtxmi as .ttf files.\
\
The lowercase upright and italic greek letters from txmia.ttf and rtxmi.ttf, respectively, were then added to the TeXGyreHeros upright and italic truetype font files.  The uppercase upright greek letters from txmia.ttf were added to both TeXGyreHeros upright and italic truetype font files.\
\
I then placed the TeXGyreHerosTXfonts.ttf files in my mpl-data/fonts/ttf directory, rebuilt my font lists, and specified "TeXGyreHerosTXfonts" as my default font in Matplotlib. However, Matplotlib could not find TeXGyreHerosTXfonts. After much playing around, I found that the TeXGyreHerosTXfonts.tff files had an attribute called "Preferred Family". (In FontForge, go to Element > Font Info > TTF Names.) The "Preferred Family" was "TeX Gyre Heros" (with spaces between each word). I supplied Matplotlib the font filename, "TeXGyreHerosTXfonts". Once I deleted the "Preferred Family" attribute, then everything worked correctly.}